<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-751-864  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 751 864.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  Sept 28 1989 v15 n20 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Futurists share ideas at ITAC meeting. (Information TechnologyAssociation of Canada)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Powell, Doug.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Five futurists assess the impact of future technologies on societyat the annual meeting of the Information Technology Assn ofCanada.andP;  Stewart Brand described the implications of work onvirtual reality being done at the Media Lab at MIT.andP;  John Gage,dir of the science office at Sun Microsystems Inc, related Sun'sgoal of creating a common working environment that would rendercurrent 'plumbing' and data conversion problems obsolete.andP;  EricDrexler outlined the revolutionary idea of 'nanotechnology,' inwhich inexpensive control of the structure of matter would makethe manufacture of devices on an atom-by-atom basis feasible.andO;James Burke propounded his views of the future of natural andartificial language processing.andP;  Toshiba Corp senior VP SakaeShimizu described products in development or on the market,including a laptop computer with workstation-quality graphics.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Information Technology Association of CanadaFuture TechnologiesFuture of Computing.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   John Gage. (portrait)Person:    Brand, Stewart (addresses, essays, lectures); Gage, John(addresses, essays, lectures); Burke, James (addresses, essays,lectures); Drexler, Eric (addresses, essays, lectures); Shimizu,Sakae (addresses, essays, lectures).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>